
MediaPipe demonstrated both excellent agreement with the reference system and also strong resolution in tracking within-subject changes in COM path length across different perturbations. 

In contrast, both RTMPose and ViTPose demonstrated poor agreement with rhe reference system, with ICC < 0.10, substantially high bias and wide limits of agreement. Sensitivity to different perturbations was poor, with r-squared < 0.40 for both trackers. 

RTMPose and ViTPose both have visible jitter in joint center positions, while MediaPipe demonstrates smoother trajectories when used on 'video mode'. One contributer to this could be the one-euro filter @casiez1FilterSimple2012 used by MediaPipe, an adaptive low-pass filter that lowers the cutoff frequency at lower speeds, reducing jitter at the expense of lag, while increasing the cutoff frequency at higher speeds to reduce lag. For balance tasks where the shift in movement is small, noise in RTMPose and ViTPose may dominate the signal, while the one-euro filter in MediaPipe may be able to preserve the signal by reducing noise. Thus, for activities where sensitivity to small shifts in posture, particularly in static balance tasks, is important, MediaPipe may be the most appropriate option. However, future work could also look at the implementation of one-euro or similar filters for RTMPose and ViTPose to see if this improves their performance in balance tasks. 